Data Preparation¶

Fixing Class Imbalance¶

In [10]:
# This value generated by the weight distribution class that need to be taken into account when training the model or to prevent biases.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get counts per class
train_counts = np.bincount(train_generator.classes)
class_labels = list(train_generator.class_indices.keys())

# Convert to numpy array for easy masking
train_counts = np.array(train_counts)
class_labels = np.array(class_labels)

# Exclude classes with too few samples
exclude_classes = ["beetle_oedem", "mecoptera_scorpionfly"]
mask = ~np.isin(class_labels, exclude_classes)

filtered_labels = class_labels[mask]
filtered_counts = train_counts[mask]

# Target number of images per class
target_images = 50

# Calculate class weights so that each class is scaled to 50
# Example: if a class has 200 images, weight = 50 / 200 = 0.25
class_weights = target_images / filtered_counts
class_weights = np.round(class_weights, 3)  # Rounded for readability

# Show calculated weights
for label, weight in zip(filtered_labels, class_weights):
    print(f"{label}: {weight}")

# Optional: visualize adjusted "equalized" distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.barh(filtered_labels, filtered_counts * class_weights, color="lightgreen")
plt.xlabel("Weighted Image Count (Target = 50)")
plt.ylabel("Insect Class")
plt.title("Adjusted Class Distribution (Weighted to 50 Images Each)")
plt.show()

Model Training¶

Insect Classification via Transfer Learning (23 Classes)¶

  • Train a 23-class image classifier using transfer learning and evaluate it properly.
  • Split: 70% train, 20% validation, 10% test (stratified by class).
  • Training: Start from an ImageNet-pretrained backbone and fine-tune.
  • Model selection & checkpointing: Select the best checkpoint on the validation set (early stopping); report final scores on the held-out test set with a confusion matrix.

Model choice¶

Use Ultralytics Classify with a timm EfficientNet-B0 backbone (ImageNet-pretrained).
(It’s simple, fast, and strong for small/medium datasets. We can later try efficientnet_v2_s if needed.)

Data layout¶

Input (raw): one folder per class (e.g., dataset_raw/<class_name>/*.jpg).
Output (prepared): dataset_insects/{train,val,test}/<class_name>/*.jpg.

Training settings (Ultralytics)¶

imgsz=384, epochs=60 (with early stopping), batch=16, lr0=3e-4, optimizer=AdamW, weight_decay=0.05, patience=10, deterministic=True, workers=0.
Standard augmentations (e.g., flip/translate/scale, RandAugment, erasing) and label smoothing for small data.

Metrics¶

During/after training: Top-1 / Top-5 accuracy on validation; final report on test (+ confusion matrix).

Prepare stratified train/val/test splits.
Sets a fixed RNG seed, then walks through each class folder in cleaned/ and copies images into train, val, and test subfolders using a 70/20/10 split (per class). This preserves class balance across splits and creates the Ultralytics-friendly directory layout.

In [11]:
import shutil, random
from pathlib import Path

random.seed(42)

SRC = Path("../datasets/initialTestDataSetV2/cleaned")      
DST = Path("../datasets/initialTestDataSetV2/train_val_test_split")
splits = {"train": 0.7, "val": 0.2, "test": 0.1}
exts = {".jpg", ".jpeg", ".png", ".bmp", ".webp"}

for s in splits:
    (DST / s).mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

for class_dir in sorted(SRC.iterdir()):
    if not class_dir.is_dir():
        continue
    images = [p for p in class_dir.iterdir() if p.suffix.lower() in exts]
    images.sort()
    random.shuffle(images)
    n = len(images)
    n_train = int(round(n * splits["train"]))
    n_val   = int(round(n * splits["val"]))
    n_test  = n - n_train - n_val

    parts = {
        "train": images[:n_train],
        "val":   images[n_train:n_train + n_val],
        "test":  images[n_train + n_val:],
    }

    for split, files in parts.items():
        out_dir = DST / split / class_dir.name
        out_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
        for f in files:
            shutil.copy2(f, out_dir / f.name)

print("Split completed.")

Split completed.

from collections import Counter
def count_split(root: Path):
    out = {}
    for split in ["train","val","test"]:
        cnt = Counter()
        for c in (root/split).iterdir():
            if c.is_dir():
                cnt[c.name] += len(list(c.glob("*")))
        out[split] = dict(cnt)
    return out

Create a balanced training subset.
Utility to build a class-balanced training set (e.g., by limiting or resampling per-class images) when class frequencies are skewed. Helps reduce bias during training on imbalanced data.

Note: After the new train_balanced folder is created, open it and visually inspect that each class folder contains the expected number of images.
If everything looks correct, you can safely delete the old train folder and rename train_balanced to train,
so that it will be used automatically during the transfer learning phase by YOLO or other Ultralytics classifiers.

In [26]:
import os, random, shutil, numpy as np
from pathlib import Path

random.seed(42)

ROOT = Path("../datasets/initialTestDataSetV2/train_val_test_split")
SRC  = ROOT / "train"
DST  = ROOT / "train_balanced"
EXTS = {".jpg", ".jpeg", ".png", ".bmp", ".webp"}

DST.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

# classes and counts
classes = sorted([d for d in SRC.iterdir() if d.is_dir()])
counts = {}
for d in classes:
    imgs = [p for p in d.iterdir() if p.is_file() and p.suffix.lower() in EXTS]
    counts[d.name] = len(imgs)

arr = np.array(list(counts.values()), dtype=int)

target = int(np.percentile(arr[arr > 0], 80)) if np.any(arr > 0) else 0
target = max(target, 16)   
target = min(target, 400)  

print(f"TARGET per class = {target}")

for cdir in classes:
    cname = cdir.name
    src_imgs = [p for p in cdir.iterdir() if p.is_file() and p.suffix.lower() in EXTS]
    n = len(src_imgs)
    if n == 0:
        print(f"[Warnings] '{cname}' empty class; skipping.")
        continue

    out = DST / cname
    out.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    for p in src_imgs:
        dst_path = out / p.name
        try:
            if not dst_path.exists():
                shutil.copy2(p, dst_path)
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"[ERROR] Original Copy: {p.name} -> {e}")

    if n < target:
        need = target - n
        base_idx = 0
        chosen = random.choices(src_imgs, k=need)
        for i, p in enumerate(chosen, start=1):
            short_name = f"dup_{i:04d}{p.suffix.lower()}"  
            dst_path = out / short_name
            try:
                while dst_path.exists():
                    base_idx += 1
                    short_name = f"dup_{i:04d}_{base_idx}{p.suffix.lower()}"
                    dst_path = out / short_name
                shutil.copy2(p, dst_path)
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"[Error] Dup is not written ({cname}): {short_name} -> {e}")

print("train_balanced is created.")

TARGET per class = 251
train_balanced is created.

Class Weights Diagnostic¶

Why was weight changed from 50 to 140?
Originally, weight=50 meant each class would have at most 50 images.
However, this caused the network to underutilize classes that had more data available (it effectively downsampled them).
Setting weight=140 switches the logic to oversampling:
now classes with fewer than 140 images are duplicated until they reach 140,
ensuring that the model sees roughly the same number of samples per class without discarding data from rich classes.
This helps reduce class imbalance while keeping the dataset size sufficient for transfer learning stability.

In [15]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

train_root = ROOT / "train"
classes = sorted([d.name for d in train_root.iterdir() if d.is_dir()])
counts = np.array([len(list((train_root / c).iterdir())) for c in classes])
target = counts.mean()
weights = np.round(target / np.maximum(counts, 1), 3)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.barh(classes, counts * weights, color='lightgreen')
plt.title("Weighted Class Distribution (Diagnostic)")

plt.ylabel("Class")

import sys, subprocess, pkg_resources

def ensure(pkg_spec: str):
    try:
        pkg_resources.require(pkg_spec)
        print(f"OK  {pkg_spec}")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"INSTALL {pkg_spec} …")
        subprocess.check_call([sys.executable, "-m", "pip", "install", "-qU", pkg_spec])
        pkg_resources.require(pkg_spec)
        print(f"OK  {pkg_spec}")

Evaluation¶

Evaluate the best checkpoint on the held-out test set.
Loads best.pt and runs inference on split="test" to report final Top-1/Top-5 accuracy. Also makes the confusion matrix available via metrics.confusion_matrix for detailed per-class analysis.

Understanding Top-1 and Top-5 Accuracy¶

Top-1 accuracy measures how often the model’s single highest-probability prediction is correct —
that is, the predicted class exactly matches the true label.

Top-5 accuracy measures how often the true label appears within the model’s five most confident predictions.
This metric is useful for multi-class problems (like our 23-class insect dataset),
because even if the model’s top guess is wrong, it might still rank the correct class among its top 5 choices —
showing that it “almost knew” the answer.

Example:
If an image of a dragonfly gets predictions
["bee", "wasp", "dragonfly", "butterfly", "ant"],
then it counts as Top-1 incorrect but Top-5 correct.

BEST = r"runs/classify/train2/weights/best.pt"  # the path for the best model

model = YOLO(BEST)
metrics = model.val(data=DATA_DIR, split="test", imgsz=384, device=0, workers=0)

print("top1:", metrics.top1)
print("top5:", metrics.top5)
